## Appendix D. Proofs of Geometric Realizations (Chapter 9)

### D.1 Proof of Proposition 9.1 (Firm Nonexpansiveness of Proximal Maps)

**Proposition 9.1.** On a Hadamard manifold, $\operatorname{prox}_{\lambda \phi}$ is firmly nonexpansive.

**Proof.**
Let $u = \operatorname{prox}_{\lambda \phi}(p)$ and $v = \operatorname{prox}_{\lambda \phi}(q)$.
The optimality conditions are:
$$ -\lambda \nabla \phi(u) \in \exp_u^{-1}(p), \quad -\lambda \nabla \phi(v) \in \exp_v^{-1}(q). $$
In Hadamard manifolds, this implies the variational inequality [5, Theorem 5.1.2]:
$$ \langle \exp_u^{-1}(p), \exp_u^{-1}(w) \rangle \ge \lambda (\phi(w) - \phi(u)) \quad \forall w \in \mathcal{M}. $$
Setting $w=v$ for the first inequality and $w=u$ for the second:
$$ \langle \exp_u^{-1}(p), \exp_u^{-1}(v) \rangle \ge \lambda (\phi(v) - \phi(u)), $$
$$ \langle \exp_v^{-1}(q), \exp_v^{-1}(u) \rangle \ge \lambda (\phi(u) - \phi(v)). $$
Summing these:
$$ \langle \exp_u^{-1}(p), \exp_u^{-1}(v) \rangle + \langle \exp_v^{-1}(q), \exp_v^{-1}(u) \rangle \ge 0. $$
Using the CAT(0) inequality for quadruples (specifically the monotonicity of the logarithmic map):
$$ d_g^2(u, v) \le \langle \exp_u^{-1}(p), \exp_u^{-1}(v) \rangle - \langle \exp_v^{-1}(q), \exp_v^{-1}(u) \rangle. $$
Combining with the sum inequality yields the firm nonexpansiveness condition:
$$ d_g^2(u, v) \le \langle \exp_u^{-1}(p) - \exp_v^{-1}(q), \exp_u^{-1}(v) \rangle. $$
This translates to the metric inequality in Definition 3.4. ∎

